******
[2] Culling and animal welfare issues
Date: Sun 9 Jan 2011
Source: Times Live (South Africa), Reuters [edited]
<http://www.timeslive.co.za/world/article839713.ece/Outrage-as-South-Korea-battles-disease>


Pigs are being culled by the hundreds of thousands to halt the spread
of infections.

Sky News quoted a spokesman of an animal protection organisation,
Compassion in World Farming, as saying: "This is totally contrary to
international guidelines on humane culling, which the Korean
government endorsed 5 years ago. We urge the Korean government to end
this horrendous practice at once and to ensure that, if animals are
culled, it is done humanely."

The outbreaks of the disease threaten to keep pushing up prices of
beef and pork in Asia's 4th-largest economy. Hundreds of thousands of
officials have been working day and night to slaughter the animals
and vaccinate more than 1.2 million more.

About 1.1 million animals have been destroyed, or about 8 per cent of
South Korea's pigs and cattle [This statement is in need of further
clarification, since culling figures have not become available for
each species separately. - Mod.AS]

The government said: "[The] beef supply is getting unstable as
slaughter places are shut down, and the transfer of animals is
blocked due to foot and mouth disease."

The government said that, with the Chinese New Year being celebrated
from 2 to 6 Feb 2011, beef prices were "expected to continue rising
through a high-demand season," the country's largest holiday. Retail
prices of beef and pork on Thursday [6 Jan 2011] soared 10 and 11 per
cent respectively from Wednesday.

President Lee Myung-bak on Thursday [6 Jan 2011] called an emergency
cabinet meeting to discuss the disease, which affects sheep, cows,
and pigs. However, the disease and meat from infected animals are not
harmful to humans.

